Here are both approaches for MAUI Shell navigation with `IQueryAttributable`:

**1. Register the route:**
```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
Routing.RegisterRoute("ProductDetailsPage", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
```

**2. Navigate — simple string parameter:**
```csharp
// From ProductListPage or its ViewModel
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"ProductDetailsPage?productId={product.Id}");
}
```

**3. Navigate — passing the full object:**
```csharp
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    var navParams = new Dictionary<string, object>
    {
        { "product", product }
    };
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("ProductDetailsPage", navParams);
}
```

**4. Receive both on the ViewModel with `IQueryAttributable`:**
```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    private string _productId;
    private Product _product;

    public string ProductId { get => _productId; set => SetProperty(ref _productId, value); }
    public Product Product { get => _product; set => SetProperty(ref _product, value); }

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach 1: simple string parameter
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var id))
        {
            ProductId = id.ToString();
            // Load full product from a service, etc.
        }

        // Approach 2: full object (passed via Dictionary<string, object>)
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product product)
        {
            Product = product;
            ProductId = product.Id;
        }
    }
}
```

**5. Wire up the page:**
```xml
<!-- ProductDetailsPage.xaml -->
<ContentPage xmlns:vm="clr-namespace:MyApp.ViewModels">
    <ContentPage.BindingContext>
        <vm:ProductDetailsViewModel />
    </ContentPage.BindingContext>
    <Label Text="{Binding Product.Name}" />
</ContentPage>
```

**Key differences:**

| | String param | Object param |
|---|---|---|
| **Navigation call** | `GoToAsync($"...?id={val}")` | `GoToAsync("...", dictWithObject)` |
| **Received as** | `object` (boxed string) | Original `Product` reference |
| **URI-safe** | Yes | No — requires the dictionary overload |

Use the string approach for deep links / URI-based navigation. Use the object approach when you already have the data in memory and want to avoid a redundant lookup.
